{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014X9ip1pC5GokYc5znRRswY","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/input/Pan Seared Scallops.generated.21.txt"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e2088c48-e314-46b0-b268-2e09887642e2","uuid":"40e56198-44a7-473c-be0e-48d25154c5b6","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/input/Pan Seared Scallops.generated.21.txt","content":"Pan Seared Scallops\n\nScallops are nature's gift to the impatient cook—they transform in mere minutes from raw to perfectly cooked, tender and sweet. The trick is to pat them bone-dry before searing; moisture is the enemy of a golden crust. A screaming-hot pan and a touch of butter create that coveted golden shell while keeping the interior delicate. This elegant preparation appears complicated but is deceptively simple, making it perfect for dinner party success. Many amateur cooks overcook scallops out of fear, but a quick sear is all that's required.\n\nINGREDIENTS:\n1.5 lb large sea scallops (about 8-10 scallops)\nSalt and pepper\n2 tablespoons butter\n2 tablespoons olive oil\n3 cloves garlic, minced\n2 tablespoons dry white wine\n2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice\n¼ cup fresh parsley, chopped\nLemon wedges for serving\n\nINSTRUCTIONS:\n1. Pat scallops dry with paper towels\n2. Season generously with salt and pepper on both sides\n3. Heat butter and oil in large skillet over high heat until very hot\n4. Working in batches if needed, place scallops flat side down\n5. Sear without moving for 2-3 minutes until golden crust forms\n6. Flip and sear other side 1-2 minutes more\n7. Remove scallops to plate\n8. Add garlic to pan and cook 30 seconds\n9. Add wine and lemon juice, scraping up browned bits\n10. Return scallops to pan briefly to coat with sauce\n11. Garnish with parsley and serve with lemon wedges\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null}}
